WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.400 --> 00:00:03.920
In this video, I'm going to walk you through setting up a virtual environment on a Windows

2
00:00:03.920 --> 00:00:08.800
machine. Now, if you already closed out your VS Code window, go ahead and open up a new one and

3
00:00:08.800 --> 00:00:14.000
make sure you open up the specific directory we created a couple of lessons ago. Now what we want to

4
00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:18.959
do is we want to select a terminal, and we want to select new terminal. And this is an awesome feature

5
00:00:18.959 --> 00:00:24.480
with VS Code, it allows us to have an integrated terminal within our VS Code window.

6
00:00:24.480 --> 00:00:28.959
And this terminal is fundamentally no different than a regular terminal within Windows.

7
00:00:28.959 --> 00:00:33.040
It's just built into VS Code so that we don't have to keep flipping between different windows. And if you

8
00:00:33.040 --> 00:00:37.439
actually take a look at this right column, we can have multiple terminals open and we can even use

9
00:00:37.439 --> 00:00:41.919
different terminals. So the default one on this machine happens to be PowerShell. But you can also

10
00:00:41.919 --> 00:00:45.040
use Command Prompt if that's what you prefer. So if you select Command Prompt, it's going to create

11
00:00:45.040 --> 00:00:49.040
a new terminal. And you can see that this is a traditional command prompt, I'm going to use this

12
00:00:49.040 --> 00:00:52.799
one because that's the one I normally use. However, if you're more comfortable with PowerShell, feel

13
00:00:52.799 --> 00:00:58.639
free to use that. Now the command to actually create a virtual environment within Windows

14
00:00:58.639 --> 00:01:06.480
is python3 -m venv. So that stands for virtual environment. And then you want to give

15
00:01:06.480 --> 00:01:10.800
it a name. So give whatever name you want for your virtual environment, you could name it after your

16
00:01:10.800 --> 00:01:17.760
project name, or you could just do what I do, which is just call it venv. And what I like to do

17
00:01:17.760 --> 00:01:22.000
is for all of my projects, I give it the same exact name. And that's perfectly okay, because

18
00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:27.599
this virtual environment is going to be isolated to this project directory. And so even though

19
00:01:27.599 --> 00:01:31.919
this project has a virtual environment named venv, I can create another virtual environment

20
00:01:31.919 --> 00:01:36.080
in any other project with the same exact name, they're all going to be isolated to that specific

21
00:01:36.080 --> 00:01:41.519
project folder. So go ahead and hit enter. And take a look over here, you'll see that a folder

22
00:01:41.519 --> 00:01:47.199
was created called venv or VNV. And that's going to be the name of this folder is

23
00:01:47.199 --> 00:01:51.760
always going to refer to whatever name you gave it. So if I named this cookies, this would open

24
00:01:51.760 --> 00:01:55.760
up a new folder called cookies. And if you want you can take a look at what's in here. And if you

25
00:01:55.760 --> 00:02:00.320
go under Scripts specifically, you'll notice that we've got our Python executable. So this is going

26
00:02:00.320 --> 00:02:06.480
to act as our new interpreter. And so what we want to do is right now we are using our global

27
00:02:06.480 --> 00:02:11.039
interpreter. And we want to change that we don't want to use the global one, we want to use the

28
00:02:11.039 --> 00:02:16.639
specific one in our virtual environment. And that way we can install packages that are exclusive to

29
00:02:16.639 --> 00:02:21.600
just this specific virtual environment. And so to do that, go ahead and select View once again.

30
00:02:21.679 --> 00:02:26.800
And we want to go to command palette, and then search for Python, select interpreter,

31
00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:32.559
as usual. And then you'll see the one we're currently using, but we want to pass in our

32
00:02:32.559 --> 00:02:37.600
newest one. So select, enter interpreter path. And then we want to give it the path to our

33
00:02:37.600 --> 00:02:42.960
interpreter, which is the path from the root of our project directory to this Python.exe file,

34
00:02:42.960 --> 00:02:47.919
we're going to say dot, which is our current folder. So this is going to be the FastAPI folder.

35
00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:51.039
And then within here, we want to go into scripts.

36
00:02:53.039 --> 00:02:58.559
And then within scripts, well, sorry, we want to go into the virtual environment folder, then scripts.

37
00:03:00.080 --> 00:03:05.600
And then python.exe, go ahead and hit enter. And then if you look down here, you'll see that

38
00:03:05.600 --> 00:03:11.039
this gets updated. So now we're still using 3.9.6. But we're using our virtual environment.

39
00:03:12.080 --> 00:03:16.639
And so that's all we need to do. And it should remember this every time we open up our project,

40
00:03:16.639 --> 00:03:20.240
however, double check every time you open up just to make sure you're using that if it's

41
00:03:20.240 --> 00:03:26.240
for some reason moved back to the default one, just do the same process. Now, the second thing

42
00:03:26.240 --> 00:03:29.600
that we need to do is we need to make sure our terminal is also using the virtual environment.

43
00:03:30.479 --> 00:03:33.039
And so what we want to do to do that is just type in

44
00:03:35.119 --> 00:03:40.160
the path to this specific activate.bat file, this is going to activate that virtual

45
00:03:40.160 --> 00:03:46.479
environment within our command line as well. So I'm going to say virtualenv.

46
00:03:48.320 --> 00:03:54.320
And then we want to pass in our scripts folder, and then activate.bat,

47
00:03:56.559 --> 00:04:01.759
hit enter. And then notice what's changed, right? So when you're using a virtual environment,

48
00:04:01.759 --> 00:04:04.720
right, you're going to see the name of the virtual environment to the side of it.

49
00:04:04.720 --> 00:04:08.639
So always double-check whenever you start up VS Code, and you start up your project

50
00:04:08.639 --> 00:04:12.720
that this is enabled. If you don't see this, then just run the same exact command. And that's

51
00:04:12.720 --> 00:04:16.880
going to reactivate the virtual environment. And so at this point, we are good to go with

52
00:04:16.880 --> 00:04:19.440
our virtual environment and we can start coding out our project.
